Unchanged Impact to our thesis
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

Initial View \((= / + )\) : Recall we left LQ with the view that our Overweight call could take longer to play out than anticipated considering incremental tariffs & a potentially choppy turnaround path at BR & Athleta (more here). In our view, that dynamic mostly played out in 2Q25 results, with 1) Athleta performance remaining challenged, missing sales growth/comp estimates, & impacting total company 2Q GM, & 2) mgmt. trimming FY guidance further on incremental tariffs. That said, 1) proof points that mgmt.'s brand reinvigoration strategies are working continued to be on display at other brands in 2Q, 2) profitability is marching higher ex- tariffs, 3) we see a rare potential positive NTM EPS revision path against lowered FY guidance & considering mgmt.'s constructive '26e tariff commentary, & 4) valuation remains amongst the lowest in our coverage - all of which make for reasons to remain Overweight rated. We are reviewing our estimates & PT.

2Q25 \((= / - )\) : EPS came in a touch better than Street forecasts & implied guidance primarily on lower- than- expected SG&A (57c vs. Street 55c & \(\sim 50 - 55c\) guidance), which mgmt. attributed to a technology investment spending shift into 3Q25 (i.e., lower- quality beat). More specifically, while GAP's topline narrative was mostly unchanged from recent trend in the quarter - with three of four brands continuing their consistent, positive comp trajectories as brand reinvigoration efforts shine - GM underperformance vs. consensus & mgmt. guidance stood out to the downside (41.2% vs. Street 41.9% & guidance \(\sim 41.8\%\) ). This below- expectations GM outcome stemmed from unexpected incremental promotional actions to support the Athleta reset, where 1) comps fell - 9% - similar to 1Q, despite an easier q/q compare, & 2) mgmt. has appointed the leadership. This result likely fuels bears' fears that there's limited GM expansion ahead for GAP, though mgmt.'s underlying FY GM commentary (ex- tariffs) was constructive (more below). Altogether, while we view the 2Q25 EPS result as less impressive than recent quarters, we also think outperformance amidst incremental headwinds speaks to continued mgmt. discipline - a theme in the \(\sim 1.2Y\) .

3Q25 Guidance \((= )\) : Mgmt. set initial 3Q25 revenue growth guidance in- line with the Street on strong QTD trends \((+2\%\) y/y), but profitability guidance below \((\sim 7.5\%\) OM vs. consensus 8.4%). This worse 3Q profitability outlook reflects below- consensus GM & SG&A expectations - a function of 1) at the midpoint, \(\sim 200\) bps of tariff impacts, partially offset by \(\sim 40\) bps of underlying GM expansion, & 2) the aforementioned technology- related investment flipping to a headwind in 3Q & 4Q. At first glance, initial 3Q25 guidance screens beat- able to us considering it embeds 1)

a \(\sim 2\) pt q/q topline growth acceleration on a \(\sim 3\) pt easier compare (& we've observed a 4 pt q/q acceleration in high frequency demand data...), 2) implied +LSD \(\%\) y/y SG&A growth vs. 1H declines, & 3) potentially more mitigate- able tariff effects on GM - if recent industry trend/narrative holds true. Bigger picture, we note GAP has successfully managed to quarterly profitability/EPS outperformance consistently in the \(\sim L2Y\) , & we suspect that could remain the case in 3Q25.

FY Guidance (=): Mgmt. reiterated FY topline growth guidance in- line with Street expectations (+1- 2% y/y vs. consensus +2%), but trimmed FY OM/EPS guidance below prior & Street on incremental tariffs (6.7- 7.0% vs. \(\sim 7.1\%\) prior & Street 7.0%). We note excluding tariffs, mgmt.'s revised FY profitability outlook encouragingly reflects y/y margin expansion ( \(\sim 7.8 - 8.1\%\) vs. \(\sim 7.1\%\) prior & '24 7.4%), & that mgmt. spoke to an ongoing margin improvement opportunity in '26e & beyond as 1) the organization potentially fully mitigates any tariff impact, & 2) brand reinvigoration strategies take further hold. Upon initial inspection, & for reasons similar to our 3Q25 guidance view (above), revised FY guidance strikes us as beat- able.

Stock Reaction (=): GAP stock recovered from - MSD % to \(\sim\) flat in AMC trading, we think reflective of 1) encouraging mgmt. commentary on the business' ability to mitigate tariff impacts in '26e & beyond, 2) further clarification on strong underlying profitability trends ex- tariffs, & 3) additional detail explaining 2Q GM underperformance.
